<jats:title>Abstract</jats:title>
				<jats:p>The aim of the study is to identify the relevant aspects of numerical analysis of impact of projectiles with soft cores into a package composed of thin flexible plies located on the plastic backing. In order to illustrate the problem, normal impact of 7.62 mm TT projectile into an unclamped package comprising 36 plies of Dyneema SB71 supported on the plastic backing was selected. The problem was solved with the use of the finite element method (FEM) with the explicit integration scheme (central difference method) of motion equations in the matrix form. Based on the conducted numerical computations, it was revealed that obtaining the extreme deformations of a projectile soft core and the backing material in Lagrangian description requires employment of adaptive methods. The proposed R-adaptive method performs its role but must be used carefully due to the mass loss which may appear during calculations.</jats:p>

Influenza: causes and incidence
subtitle: The term 'flu’ has become synonymous with the development of a clearly defined syndrome of symptoms - fever, malaise, shivering etc. These symptoms, however, are rarely caused by influenza, which is a specific illness associated with a particular set of viruses. In the first of two articles, Marie Kedzierski explores the biology of the organisms responsible

title: Influenza: virulence and management
Liver disease in babies and children
Management of viral hepatitis
subtitle: Marie Kedzierski reviews the causes and management of viral hepatitis. She emphasises the importance of nurses being familiar with the viral strains which cause the different diseases grouped under the ‘viral hepatitis’ heading, and the importance of offering informed and effective health education and advice to patients.

title: Specimen collection for virological tests
subtitle: The seemingly trivial task of preparing virological investigation specimens for storage and subsequent transportation to the laboratory is, in fact, an extremely important and skilled one, argues Marie Kedzierski. Her article explores the means of detecting various strains of organisms from different types of specimen and demonstrates the pathological processes which are associated with specific viruses

title: Diseases of the herpes viruses
subtitle: The increasing numbers of people in the community who are immunocompromised, either through the effects of drug therapy or disease processes, has led to a significant enhancement of the pathogenicity of the herpes viruses. Marie Kedzierski discusses the conditions associated with this viral group, and urges that consideration of these organisms must constitute a major part of any comprehensive health education programme
